\begin_layout Subsection
Consolidation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Qualia were a somewhat diffuse topic when they were first introduced, and
 they haven't gotten that much clearer since.
 Dennett felt this was sufficient to totally abandon the term, while Metzinger
 on the other hand gives them ontological legitimation, while still attempting
 to analyze them and saying that there is nothing atomical about them --
 they are mostly merely paradigmatic definitions of arbitrary abstraction.
 Let us look closer at how exactly their views differ.
 They both share some similarities:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Both concepts of qualia are in principle reducible.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Both concepts of qualia have distinct ways things seem to feel.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, there are important differences between their theories.
 The most striking ones:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Dennett abandons the term “qualia” altogether, while Metzinger gives the
 term 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

qualia
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

