Similarly to the PSM (see chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Being-No-One"

\end_inset

), the PMIR is merely a phenomenal model, merely an emergent, transparent
 phenomenal structure.
 It is a conscious mental model, presented phenomenally in a transparent
 manner and thus experienced as unquestionably real.
 Its content is an ongoing, episodic subject-object relation -- representing
 the system as subject through its PSM, and the object in an asymmetrical
 relation to that subject.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Kinds of Perceived Intentional Relations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The trivial description applies to a wide variety of cases, and a plethora
 of entities can be represented as object components.
 They usually fall into one of the following categories:
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
