\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "Phenomenalizing-Intentionality"

\end_inset

Phenomenalizing Intentionality
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we want to naturalize intentionality (as Metzinger wants to), phenomenalizing
 it is the necessary first step.
 Here's how he explains this:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quotation
Phenomenalizing intentionality, I would submit, may be a necessary detour,
 an indispensable first step in the project of 
\emph on
naturalizing
\emph default
 intentionality 
\emph on
tout court
\emph default
.
 Meaning and the conscious experience of meaningfulness have to be separated.
 Generally speaking, mental representations possess two kinds of content:
 phenomenal content and intentional content.
 Phenomenal content supervenes locally.
 Intentional content, in many cases, is determined by external and nonlocal
 factors.
 [...] It is important to note how intentionality [...] is 
\emph on
itself
\emph default
 depicted on the level of phenomenal content.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Citation from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Metzinger2003"

\end_inset

, page 414, emphasis his.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Part of this is obvious: Meaning and the conscious experience of meaningfulness
 (which corresponds to intentionality) are not the same things, although
 they are experienced (thus the phenomenality) as being intuitively and
 unquestionably the same.
 Metzinger now makes the argument that while we do know that phenomenal
 content supervenes locally, we do not necessarily know that intentional
 content, which refers to external entities, also supervenes locally.
 If we can show that intentional content is just a special form of phenomenal
 content, it goes without saying that intentional content supervenes locally
 and can thus potentially be naturalized.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Showing that intentional content is a special form of phenomenal content
 is of course what the theory about the PMIR is all about.
 Since all there is to intentionality is the phenomenal experience of an
 intentionality relation, it could exist completely without ontological
 counterparts to the entities represented by said intentionality relation's
 phenomenal contents.
 Intentionality could be entirely virtual, and we couldn't possibly notice.
 In fact, it is even probable that we misrepresent many things out there
 in the world, because that misrepresentation has proved to be more beneficial
 for our continued survival as a species:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quotation
This global effect [of “global immersion”] is achieved by continuously activatin
g dynamic and transparent representations of a subject-object relation,
 which episodically integrates the self-model and those perceptual, cognitive
 or volitional objects, which cause the changes in its content, by telling
 an internal story about how these changes came about.
 This story does not have to be a true story.
 It may well be a greatly simplified confabulation, which has proved to
 be functionally adequate.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Citation from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
