Dennett's Intentionality Should Be Phenomenal
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I am talking about Dennett's argumentation that intentionality is nothing
 but an ascription that happens through a stance that we take on when looking
 at entities that might exhibit inentionality.
 We remember, he says that it all comes down to whatever intentional states
 we ascribe to a target system has to be what its intentionality truly is.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This argumentation seems to be counter-intuitive to me (among many others),
 and the reason why that is appears to be two-fold:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Less importantly, it can lead to a circular argumentation culminating in
 an infinite regress.
 If something (me, for example) ascribes intentionality to something, it
 has to do so intentionally.
 There must be an intentionality ascribing the intentionality, because ascriptio
n is an intentional act.
 I guess this could be explained away by merely a different choice of words
 of course, nevertheless, I think it is important.
