\begin_layout Subsubsection
Requirements for knowledge
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I think that epistemology is, in fact, not such a complicated subject as
 we assume it to be -- and obviously, not as complicated as it seems from
 my discussion so far.
 The only way in which we can know whether a belief is not only justified,
 but also true, is if we assume things that imply verity in their very definitio
n (like intrinsic intentionality or dualism).
 Only due to these definitions and dogmatinc settings these things have
 verifying force, making the verifying force circular.
 It is the classic Münchhausen trilemma we are faced with, of course.
 When attempting to justify any argumentation, we have the choice among
 the following three alternatives:
